Runoff generation in JULES is modelled using either the standard model [is this right?], the Probability Distributed Model \citep{}, or a modified form of TOPMODEL \citep{clark_representing_2008}. The main reason to adopt the PDM and TOPMODEL schemes is to represent subgrid heterogeneity in runoff production. According to \citet{clark_representing_2008}, who applied JULES to three catchments in southern France, parameterizing JULES with either PDM or TOPMODEL may result in substantial performance gains compared with the standard runoff generation scheme.

\subsection{Probability Density Model}
In the PDM scheme the distribution of soil water storage capacity within a catchment is modelled by a probability density function (pdf). As precipitation is added to the catchment, smaller stores become saturated faster than larger stores. The portion of the catchment that is saturated may be expressed

\begin{equation}
  f_{sat} = 1 - \Big(1 - \frac{S - S_0}{S_{max} - S_0}\Big)^{\frac{b}{b+1}}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $S$ is the mean catchment soil water storage capacity, $S_0$ is the minimum soil water storage ``below which there is no surface saturation'' \citep{clark_representing_2008}, $S_{max}$ is the maximum soil water storage capacity, and $b$ is a shape parameter. Further precipitation will result in surface runoff generation over the saturated fraction of the catchment. The implementation of PDM in JULES treats the gridbox as a catchment.

\subsubsection{Parameterizing PDM}
Table~\ref{} shows the JULES parameters which are used to parameterize the PDM scheme. The PDM routines are implemented in the file $src/soil/pdm\_jls\_mod.F90$. There are three key parameters: $S_{0}$, $S_{max}$, and $b$. The first two parameters are used in JULES as a fraction, $S_{0}/S_{max}$. \citet{clark_representing_2008} set $S_{max}$ as the depth of soil considered (dz\_pdm) multiplied by the saturated volumetric water content. 

