\subsection{Topmodel}
``...the saturated fraction in TOPMODEL is derived from observed topographic characteristics and cannot be calibrated or changed'' \citep{martinez_using_2019}. In Topmodel, the variation of soil moisture in space is characterised ``in terms of the spatial distribution of the topographic index, \lambda. The pdf of \lambda is used to calculate the saturated portion of the catchment. Unlike the PDM parametersization, Topmodel estimates lateral subsurface flow. To do this, a deep water store is added beneath the standard JULES soil column. In the Topmodel parameterization used by \citep{clark_representing_2008}, ``there was no drainage through the bottom of the soil column''. I \textit{think} this must be referring to the additional layer which is inserted beneath the resolved layers when Topmodel is enabled. This is what Figure 1 of \citet{gedney_sensitivity_2003} suggests. The computed baseflow was divided between soil layers \textit{beneath the water table} according to the transmissivity of each layer.

A deep water store is added beneath the standard JULES soil column.

\section{Hydrological output variables}

\subsection{Topmodel-specific output variables}
$qbase$ is ``Gridbox baseflow (lateral subsurface runoff) (kg m-2 s-1), i.e. the sum of surface and subsurface lateral flows from all soil layers (inc. deep LSH/TOPMODEL layer).''

$qbase\_zw$ is ``Gridbox baseflow (lateral subsurface runoff) from deep LSH/TOPMODEL layer (kg m-2 s-1).''

\subsection{Output variables common to PDM and Topmodel}
$surf\_roff$ is ``Gridbox surface runoff (kg m-2 s-1).''

$sub\_surf\_roff$ is ``Gridbox sub-surface runoff (kg m-2 s-1).''. According to Alberto Martinez de la Torre, in PDM this is free drainage from the bottom of the resolved soil layers (personal communication, 08-04-2019). Unclear what the difference is between $qbase\_zw$ and $sub\_surf\_roff$ when Topmodel is enabled [TODO: run simple experiment to check this].

\section{Discussion}
On the basis of a sensitivity analysis, \citep{martinez_using_2019} reported that the PDM approach was most suited to modelling streamflow in three UK catchments. 

